featured_reviews.review_id:
Built in about 1561-2 CE, this relatively little-known mosque is one of the rare medieval buildings in Delhi that was built under the aegis of a woman: one of Akbar's wet nurses, Maham Anga, had it constructed. The name of the mosque 'Khair-ul-Manazil', means 'best of houses'. In the 16th century and till later, the mosque premises also housed a madarsa, of which you can still see ruined rows of double-storeyed cells surrounding the courtyard on two sides.

The large sehan or courtyard contains a shallow tank for wazu (ritual ablutions) and a now-closed well beside it. The mosque is still functional, so if you decide to go into the mosque (beyond the sehan), please take off footwear. There is a sign here to this effect.

The interior of the mosque is worth seeing: even though parts of the beautifully worked plaster and intricate coloured tile work has now disappeared, there's enough still left to make this very striking.

The gateway of the masjid was made by red sandstone following Mughal architecture, but the inside structure of the building was made in Delhi Sultanate pattern. The mosque's design seamlessly blends traditional Islamic architecture with modern elements, creating a harmonious and inviting atmosphere. This structure was built by one of the most influential and powerful women of Akbar's court Maham Anga who was Emperor Akbar's wet nurse cum foster mother.

Currently the masjid is protected and maintained by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI). Presently the building is under protection of Archaeological Survey of India.

Presently this building is under the protection of the Archaeological Survey of India.

Built around 1561 CE by Maham Anga, wet nurse of Mughal Emperor Akbar, this building originally included a Madrasa (Islamic School) along its courtyard which has mostly collapsed. The Mosque structure seems to be intact but in need of conservation. Tiny bits of the original Central Asian themed blue tile & mosaic work remains along the main arch of the mosque.
There is no parking but you can park opposite the road at the National Zoological Park. Everything is flat so persons of reduced mobility can easily walk in. Being a place of worship, do dress modestly, no shorts for men or short dresses for women & avoid going on a Friday as most worshippers would be there on that day.

featured_reviews.review_id:
It was built by Mughal Emperor Shah Jahanbetween 1644 and 1656 at a cost of 1 million rupees, and was inaugurated by an Imam from Bukhara, present-day Uzbekistan. The mosque was completed in 1656 AD with three great gates, four towers and two 40 metres high minaretsconstructed with strips of red sandstone and white marble. The courtyard can accommodate more than 25,000 people. There are three domes on the terrace which are surrounded by the two minarets. On the floor, a total of 899 black borders are marked for worshippers. The architectural plan of Badshahi Masjid, built by Shah Jahan's son Aurangzeb at Lahore, Pakistan, is similar to the Jama Masjid.

HistoryEdit

Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan built the Jama Masjid between 1644 and 1656. It was constructed by more than 5000 workers. It was originally called Masjid-i-Jahan Numa, meaning 'mosque commanding view of the world'. The construction was done under the supervision of Saadullah Khan, wazir (or prime minister) during Shah Jahan's reign. The cost of the construction at the time was one million Rupees.[1] Shah Jahan also built the Taj Mahal, at Agra and the Red Fortin New Delhi, which stands opposite the Jama Masjid.

The Jama Masjid was completed in 1656 AD (1066 AH).[1] The mosque was inaugurated by an Imam Bukhari, a mullah from Bukhara, Uzbekistan, on 23 July 1656, on the invitation from Shah Jahan.[2]About 25,000 people can pray in the courtyard at a time .[3][4] The mosque is commonly called "Jama" which means Friday.[1]

After the British victory in the Revolt of 1857, they confiscated the mosque and stationed their soldiers there. They also wanted to destroy the mosque as an act of punishment to the city. But due to opposition faced, the demolition was not done.[5]

The iconic mosque is one of the last monuments built under Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan. After the construction of the monument in 1656, it remained the royal mosque of the emperors until the end of the Mughal period.

During 1948, the last Nizam of Hyderabad, Asaf Jah VII was asked for a donation of Rs75,000 to repair one-fourth of the mosque floor. The Nizam instead sanctioned Rs3 lakh, stating that the remaining three-fourths of the mosque should not look old.

featured_reviews.review_id: This mosque is situated in the street beside the popular Tanki Road. It is three storey mosque having recently re-built and construction and renovation work is still going on. Wazukhana is at the ground floor where Namaz is offered and led by the Imam. No urinal or washroom facility is available here. Five times prayers and Friday prayers are conducted and offered regularly by the Muslims here. All three stories are mostly packed on Fridays at the time of Juma prayer. The locality comprises of mixed population majority being the non-Muslims. The visitors, the Imam and the Committee members of this mosque are the followers of Bareilvy sect of Sunni Islam. However, the Muslims from all sects including the Shia brothers (although very few in number) do visit this mosque to offer prayers. The Committee of the mosque is bringing up a Madarsa for the Islamic education of the children for which they are raising funds as well. The inhabitants near the mosque are mostly cooperative and friendly. Local women among whom mostly are the non-Muslims, visit this mosque on daily basis at the time of Maghrib (i.e. the sunset time prayer) to seek the blessings or dua of the Imam. The street in which this mosque is located, is a narrow one, hence no space for car entry or parking, however, two wheelers are parked near the mosque.

The mountain was situated in a quiet peaceful place, The garden was very calming and relaxing.
was closed when I visited this place.

The mosque located inside the Siri Fort is known as the Mohammed Wali Masjid. Although the mosque was built much later, sometime around the 15th century by one of the Lodhi rulers (1451-1526 AD), it is a beautiful structure made from finely cut stone slabs.
In the center of the mosque, there is a dome-shaped structure, which is a common feature of mosques.
The east facade of the mosque is adorned with blue tiles.
